Class ReflectiveConfigGroup

  • All Implemented Interfaces:

    Direct Known Subclasses:

    public abstract class ReflectiveConfigGroup
extends ConfigGroup
implements MatsimExtensionPoint
    A module using reflection for easy implementation of config groups.

    This class takes care of all the housekeeping tasks that you normally have to manually implement when extending ConfigGroup (usually forgetting half of it).

    For each field in the xml file, just implement a setter taking one of the following types as parameter:
    • a String,
    • a primitive data type or a "primitive wrapper" type (such as Double or Integer),
    • an enumeration type
    and a getter returning an Object or primitive type which String representation must be written to the xml file, and annotate them with the ReflectiveConfigGroup.StringSetter and ReflectiveConfigGroup.StringGetter annotation types.
    Those annotations take a mandatory String argument, which is the parameter name in the xml.

    In most of the cases (for Strings, primitive types and enums), annotating the actual setters and getters is fine. Sometimes (When the Object.toString() method returns the right String representation, for instance for Ids), one needs to implement a specific "String" setter, but can annotate the normal getter. Sometimes (for instance when handling collections) one needs specific conversion bothways. In those cases, just separate actual setters/getters and "string" setters/getters.
    Note that there is no restriction on access modifiers for those methods: they can even be private, if for instance you do not want to confuse the users with dozens of methods of the type "getStringRepresentationOfParameterX()" or "setParameterXFromStringRepresentation( String v )".
    A commented example can be found at tutorial.programming.reflectiveConfigGroup.MyConfigGroup.

    If something is wrong (missing setter or getter, wrong parameter or return type), an ReflectiveConfigGroup.InconsistentModuleException will be thrown at construction.

    thibautd

        storeUnknownParametersAsStrings - if true, when no annotated getter or setter is found for a parameter name, the parameters are stored using the default ConfigGroup behavior. This is not that safe, so be careful.

      • getComments

        public Map<String,String> getComments()
        Comments for parameters which setter get an enum type are automatically generated, containing a list of possible values. They can be overriden by subclasses without problems.
        it is recommended for subclasses to get this map using super.getComments() and fill it with additional comments, rather than generate an empty map.
